doc.after: From 1853, the Riverina was linked to markets through a series of riverboats along the Murray and Murrumbidgee to the river ports of Mannum and Goolwa in South Australia[37][38] and from 1864, to Echuca connected by rail to Melbourne.[39] Riverboats reached as far upstream as Gundagai and Albury and towns such as Darlington Point, Narrandera and Moulamein became important river ports.[15][27][36][40] The riverboat era peaked in the twenty years from 1870â1890, declining with the coming of the railway and finally ending with the disruption to the workforce caused by World War I.[40]
